V1: Proposal of Software-interrupt MSI Controller for AIA

Guo Ren
  • All Messages By This Member
Jan 19   #801  

Software MSI Controller for AIA

An SMSIC (Software-interrupt MSI Controller) is an optional RISC-V hardware component closely coupled to a hart; there is one SMSIC per hart. An SMSIC receives incoming message-signaled interrupts (MSIs) for a hart’s software interrupt, and raises related states for CSR_MIP.MSIP, CSR_SIP.SSIP, CSR_VSIP.SSIP and CSR_HIP.VSSIP. The SMSIC has one or more memory-mapped registers in the machine’s address space for receiving software MSIs, and introduces no new CSR.

Motivation

AIA is a message-signaled interrupt (MSI) solution designed for the RISC-V External interrupt. However, due to its lack of native support for Software-Interrupt. IPIs are forced to share interrupt numbers with external interrupts. This allows any MSI-capable device to forge an IPI by sending a specific interrupt number, which the system cannot easily distinguish or block, creating a serious security vulnerability.
Furthermore, in large-scale systems, IPIs occur far more frequently and at higher volume than device MSI interrupts. Therefore, architecturally separating IPIs from external interrupts not only aligns with the original intent of the RISC-V Privileged Specification but also enables potential microarchitectural improvement to reduce IPI transaction pressure on large NoC systems (D2D or S2S).

Interrupt files

In a RISC-V system, MSIs are directed not just to a specific hart but to a specific privilege level of a specific hart, such as machine or supervisor level. Furthermore, when a hart implements the H extension, an SMSIC may optionally allow MSIs to be directed to a specific virtual hart at the virtual supervisor (VS) level.
For each privilege level or virtual privilege level to which MSIs may be directed at a hart,  whose SMSIC contains a separate interrupt file. Assuming a hart implements supervisor mode, its SMSIC has at least two interrupt files: one for machine-level interrupts and the other for supervisor-level interrupts. When a hart also implements the H extension, its SMSIC may have additional interrupt files for virtual harts, called guest interrupt files. The number of guest interrupt files an SMSIC has for virtual harts is exactly GEILEN, the number of supported guest external interrupts, as defined by the H extension. SMSIC reuses CSR_HGEIP for the hypervisor to notify the virtual machine, rather than introducing a new CSR.
Each individual interrupt file consists mainly of a single bit for recording software MSI interrupts that have arrived but are not yet serviced (interrupt-pending bits).

Memory region of the interrupt files

Each interrupt file in an SMSIC has one or two memory-mapped 32-bit registers for receiving software-interrupt MSI writes. These memory-mapped registers are located within a naturally aligned 4-KiB region (a page) of physical address space that exists for the interrupt file, i.e., one page per interrupt file. The layout of an interrupt file’s memory region is:
offset    size         register name
0x000    4 bytes   seteipnum_le
0x004    4 bytes   seteipnum_be
All other bytes in an interrupt file’s 4-KiB memory region are reserved and must be implemented as read-only zeros. Only naturally aligned 32-bit simple reads and writes are supported within an interrupt file’s memory region. Writes to read-only bytes are ignored. For other forms of access (e.g., other sizes, misaligned accesses, or AMOs), an SMSIC implementation should preferably report an access fault or bus error, but must otherwise ignore the access.

Software MSI type encoding

The Software-interrupt MSI from a hart takes the form of a naturally aligned 32-bit write by the hart, with the address and encoded value, which helps micro-arch HARTS-BITMAP optimization.
Value Encoding:
  • 00 - Ignore
  • 01 - Send software Interrupt
  • 02 - Pend software Interrupt (If not supported, the same as 01)
  • Others - The same as 01
If the HART encounters exceptions or interrupts, all pending Software Interrupts in HARTS-BITMAP would be sent.
